entry.title: [SAA] Remove unused histogram
entry.content:
Despite best intentions, this histogram isn't especially useful since

98% of records are "no opt-in, no grant", as expected. The only

possibly-interesting case is "opt-in, no grant", but this is easily

explained by auto-resolved rSA calls due to cookie settings or

similar.



In any case, this histogram is recorded once per cookie access, which

means it's skewed by clients that make more network requests. More

useful is the API.StorageAccess.RequestStorageAccess2 histogram

(recorded by renderers for each rSA call) and the

API.StorageAccess.RequestOutcome histogram (recorded by the browser

for each storage-access permission request).



An added bonus of this removal is that the SAA lookups can become

lazier; we no longer have to search through content settings unless

the appropriate CookieSettingOverride is present.



OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[API.StorageAccess.InputState]=deleted since it's less useful than other histograms; see the CL description for details.

entry.title: [//gpu] Retain Graphite WGPU textures in IOSurfaceImageBacking
entry.content:
This CL caches WGPU textures created for the Graphite device in

IOSurfaceImageBacking. Doing so is a necessary precursor to performance

optimizations.



We implement this by maintaining a cache of TextureUsage -> Texture

objects for each wgpu::Device in the backing that is populated lazily

by the Dawn representation, with this cache sitting in a struct next to

the SharedTextureMemory object that is being cached for that Device.

Doing the implementation this way ensures that this caching will

transparently work for WebGPU Devices if/when we implement caching of

the SharedTextureMemory objects for those devices in the backing.

entry.title: Add sanitizer coverage allowlist gn flag.
entry.content:
Some of our fuzzers use coverage feedback to work out which parts of the

codebase are being explored and thus make decisions to explore further

parts.



This new gn option allows us to specify an allowlist file which will

apply coverage guidance only to part of the codebase. This can make

fuzzers much quicker because they no longer need to determine coverage

for the entire binary.



Subsequent CLs may apply this allowlist to specific binaries, but for

now this is a global option which applies to everything that gets built.

entry.content:
On wayland protocol, we send physical keycode and keymap separately,

and then client app respects the keymap on receiving key events.

as CTRL+K.

With this CL, on generating fake key events, we respects the keyboard

layout.

entry.title: iwa: Properly support IWAs in `windows.create`
entry.content:
Isolated Web Apps [1] always run in standalone app browser windows and

cannot be opened in normal browser windows. This is enforced by checks

in `BrowserNavigator`, which automatically moves tabs that navigate to

an installed IWA, and that are not yet in a separate window, into a

standalone window.



The `windows.create` extension API, when used with the `url` parameter

set to an `isolated-app:` URL did not play nicely with IWAs:

It created two browser windows when launching an IWA, the first being

a normal tabbed window, and the second being a proper standalone app

window created due to the code in `BrowserNavigator`.



This CL fixes the behavior by doing two things:

1. It relaxes the restrictions in `BrowserNavigator` to allow creation

of a tab in an IWA window with `NEW_*_TAB` dispositions in addition

to the `CURRENT_TAB` disposition, if there is not yet a tab in the

IWA window.

2. It updates the `windows.create` code:

- Creates an app window for isolated-app: URLs.

- Adds an error if it is called with more than one URL and one of the

URLs is an isolated-app: URL.

- Adds an error if the isolated-app: URL is malformatted.

- Adds an error if `url` contains an isolated-app: URL and `tabId` is

set as well.

- Adds an error if `tabId` refers to an `isolated-app:` tab.

- Adds an error when trying to open a window with a `type` other than

`normal`.



[1]: https://github.com/WICG/isolated-web-apps

entry.title: [TrustedVault] Replace local keys with remote when downloading
entry.content:
Before:

Upon keys downloading Backend used to preserve all already known keys,

including those that were cleaned up from the server.



After:

Backend simply accepts remote keys (even if no new keys detected).



Why:

The server actually doesn't expect that client sends stale keys, for

example in JoinSecurityDomainRequest. This is also more consistent with

other implementations and StoreKeys() behavior.

entry.title: Mutate existing fragments when adding OOFs.
entry.content:
Rather than cloning and rebuilding fragments, we can actually just

mutate them and append the new children (and other bits of information)

directly (be it OOF children of existing fragmentainers, or

fragmentainer children of existing multicol container fragments).



This became possible with https://crrev.com/c/4535076 (May 2023), which

changed fragment children storage from a fixed-size array allocated

during fragment creation, to using a HeapVector instead.



Big shout-out to Ian for making me realize this possibility.



This removes some very complicated logic which tried to search through

the fragment tree in order to figure out how to replace the old fragment

with the cloned one.



This allows us to remove a lot of code and simplify

SimplifiedOofLayoutAlgorithm. It will still be instantiated under the

same circumstances as before, but if the fragmentainer already exists,

the fragment result from the algorithm will only be used to update (by

"merging" into) the existing fragment (and break token), and afterwards

we can just drop it on the floor.



MulticolChildInfo now just contains a break token pointer. Might want to

get rid of this class.



No behavior changes intended.

entry.title: [Files]: A different approach to slow recent sources.
entry.content:
The original approach used a sequence ID to distinguish between desired

and late callback calls. However, each source would store callback and

other parameters locally. This meant that it was possible for a slow

source to be busy for so long that if a new request came and the local

variables were overwritten, the old call would come back just in time to

use the newly set instance variable specific to the new call.



Thus we adopt a new approach. Each source can be explicitly stopped.

Each source holds a map from call ID to the context needed by that call.

If the Stop call comes, it deletes the context associated with the

given call ID. This way when a new call is made, the new context is

only accessible with the new call ID, which is unknown to the old

invocation.

entry.title: language_pack_font_service: Use real service initialisation in tests
entry.content:
Before this CL, all profile `KeyedServices` were being constructed when

the `TestingProfile` was created. However, `LanguagePackFontService` was

not being constructed because the feature was disabled by default. This

caused test failures when the feature was enabled by default, as _two_

`LanguagePackFontService`s were being created in tests - one in the

profile, in in the test.



To fix this, we enable the feature by default - to explicitly create the

service with the profile - and override the factory so a real

`LanguagePackFontService` instance is created, except with a mock

`AddFontDir` implementation.



As the tests modified preferences _before_ the `LanguagePackFontService`

was available (to test logic in the initialisation of the service), this

CL also explicitly creates a `TestingPrefServiceSyncable` to use before

the profile is available and initialised.

entry.title: Revert "Ignore drag events while waiting to exit a nested run loop."
entry.content:
This reverts commit d933cbd269533f69b334f8a3d7c32c00b8211240.



Reason for revert: The new test fails consistently on Linux Tests (Wayland):



https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20Tests%20(Wayland)/51887/overview



Original change's description:

> Ignore drag events while waiting to exit a nested run loop.

>

> Background: When dragging tabs into another window, TabDragController exits the nested run loop that was handling the window drag and resumes handling the drag session within the original, parent run loop. But that is not an atomic event - it must return control and wait for the nested run loop to exit. If any additional calls into TabDragController::Drag happen between TabDragController asking to exit the run loop and that nested run loop actually exiting, TabDragController could do unexpected things while handling those events. Notably, if it tried to start another nested run loop, this would CHECK.

>

> This CL extends TabDragController's DragState state enum to explicitly model this interval with a `kWaitingToExitRunLoop` state, so it can ignore calls to Drag during this interval.

>

> It's worth noting that some platforms (Chrome OS and Linux) will use this new state, and others (Windows and Mac) will not because they instead already use the kWaitingToDragTabs state during the same interval. These are modeled separately because they correspond to very different underlying states for the drag session - see the comments on the enum values for details.

entry.title: Move palm detector from ozone platform to evdev

PalmDetector need to be used in //ui/events/ozone/evdev/touch_event_converter_evdev.h, however, there is a dependency chain:

//ui/ozone:platform ->

//ui/ozone/platform/drm:gbm ->

We propose to move the interface class from //ui/ozone to //ui/events/ozone/evdev, and renaming it to HeatmapPalmDetector, then rename the actual implementation in //chromeos/ash/components to HeatmapPalmDetectorImpl.
